DOMAIN: Semiconductor manufacturing process

CONTEXT: A complex modern semiconductor manufacturing process is normally under constant surveillance via the monitoring of signals/variables collected from sensors and or process measurement points. However, not all of these signals are equally valuable in a specific monitoring system. The measured signals contain a combination of useful information, irrelevant information as well as noise. Engineers typically have a much larger number of signals than are actually required. If we consider each type of signal as a feature, then feature selection may be applied to identify the most relevant signals. The Process Engineers may then use these signals to determine key factors contributing to yield excursions downstream in the process. This will enable an increase in process throughput, decreased time to learning and reduce the per unit production costs. These signals can be used as features to predict the yield type. And by analysing and trying out different combinations of features, essential signals that are impacting the yield type can be identified.

DATA DESCRIPTION: sensor-data.csv : (1567, 592) The data consists of 1567 examples each with 591 features. The dataset presented in this case represents a selection of such features where each example represents a single production entity with associated measured features and the labels represent a simple pass/fail yield for in house line testing. Target column 1 corresponds to a pass and 1 corresponds to a fail and the data time stamp is for that specific test point.

PROJECT OBJECTIVE: We will build a classifier to predict the Pass/Fail yield of a particular process entity and analyse whether all the features are required to build the model or not

# Creating a function which will return the list of features which has very few unique values
def unique_values(df):  
    unq = []
    
    # Create the dataframe of feature name and the number of unique values
    for col in df.columns[:-1]:
        unq.append(len(np.unique(df[col])))

    # Seperate features with one unique value
    df_unq = pd.DataFrame(unq, index=df.columns[:-1])
    drop_list = list(df_unq[df_unq[0]<2].index)
    
    # Display features with two unique values
    for col in df_unq[df_unq[0]==2].index:
        print(col, " : ", np.unique(df[col], return_counts=True))
    
    # Add two unique values feature to drop list
    drop_list.extend(list(df_unq[df_unq[0]==2].index))
    return(drop_list)
In [3]:
# Creating a function to remove outliers
def rem_outliers(df):
    # Looping through all continous features
    for col in list(df.iloc[:, :-1].columns):

        new = []

        # Calculating upper and lower bounds
        q25, q75 = np.percentile(df[col], 25), np.percentile(df[col], 75)
        IQR = q75-q25
        threshold=IQR*1.5
        lower, upper = q25 - threshold, q75 + threshold
        
        # Calucalate mean
        mean = df[col].mean()
        # Creating a new list after Capping all outliers to upper or lower bound
        for i in df[col]:
            if i < lower:new.append(mean)
            elif i > upper:new.append(mean)
            else:new.append(i)
        
        # Changing column values to new list 
        df[col] = new
    return(df)
In [4]:
# Creating a function which will return required outputs after performing welch_ttest (unequal variance)
def ttest(x, y):
     # Welch's Test    
    t, p = ttest_ind(x, y, equal_var = False)
    return(p)

def normal_test(df):
    # Initiate lists
    significant_list = []
    drop_list = []
    
    # Performing Welch's t test on Pass and Fail groups for all independent variables
    # Running a for loop to extract each feature name individually
    for col in df.columns[:-1]:
        # Creating 2 groups based on Dependent variable labels 1 and not 1
        group1 = df[col][df["Pass/Fail"]==1]
        group2 = df[col][df["Pass/Fail"]!=1]

        # If Shapiro test clears both groups (Confidence of 90%) then perform welch test else add to drop list
        if (shapiro(group1)[1]>0.1) and (shapiro(group2)[1]>0.1):
            # Calculate p value to check if mean is significantly different
            p = ttest(group1, group2)
            
            # If p is significant at 90% confidence then add feature to significant list
            if p < 0.1:
                significant_list.append(col)
        else:
            # Add to drop list if either group is not normally distributed
            drop_list.append(col)
    return(drop_list, significant_list)

# Create a function which display Important features and also returns a list of important features
def imp_features(df):
    # create an instance for tree feature selection
    tree_clf = ExtraTreesClassifier(random_state=42)

    # first create arrays holding input and output data
    x_train = df_signal.drop("Pass/Fail", axis=1)
    y = df_signal['Pass/Fail'].replace({-1: 0})

    # fit the model
    tree_clf.fit(x_train, y)

    # Preparing variables
    importances = tree_clf.feature_importances_
    feature_names = x_train.columns
    feature_imp_dict = dict(zip(feature_names, importances))
    sorted_features = sorted(feature_imp_dict.items(), key=operator.itemgetter(1), reverse=True)
    indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1]

    # Print the feature ranking (Top 20)
    print("Feature ranking:")
    for f in range(20):
        print("feature %d : %s (%f)" % (indices[f], sorted_features[f][0], sorted_features[f][1]))

    # Plot the top 100 feature importances of the forest
    plt.figure(figsize = (20,20))
    plt.title("Feature importances")
    plt.bar(range(len(x_train.columns)), importances[indices],
           color="r", align="center")
    plt.xticks(range(len(x_train.columns)), sorted_features, rotation=90)
    plt.xlim([-1, 100])
    plt.show()
    
    return(feature_imp_dict)

Moving on from the previous observations we decide to impute the missing values. The quick approach would be to impute the missing data with mean values.
Before Imputing however we will convert Time Column to more relevant columns

In [16]:
# Initailising
idx_list = []
outliers = {}

# Looping through all continous features
for col in list(df_signal.iloc[:, :-1].columns):
    
    # checking count of outliers.
    q25, q75 = np.percentile(df_signal[col], 25), np.percentile(df_signal[col], 75)
    IQR = q75-q25
    threshold=IQR*1.5
    lower, upper = q25 - threshold, q75 + threshold
    
    # Adding information to outliers list
    outliers[col] = [lower, 
                     len([i for i in df_signal[col] if i < lower]), 
                     upper, 
                     len([i for i in df_signal[col] if i > upper])]
    
    # Creating list of indexes which are outliers
    for idx in df_signal[col].index:
        if df_signal.loc[idx, col] < lower:idx_list.append(idx)
        elif df_signal.loc[idx, col] > upper:idx_list.append(idx)

#     # Removing duplicates from index list
#     idx_list = list(set(idx_list))

4 rows 480 columns

It is apparent from the information above that we cannot choose to drop outliers since we will end up dropping all records. So the next best thing is to either cap outliers or to change the outliers to mean values. Since we also know that most features are not normally distributed, also that some features have a lot of outliers. So we will not add to the problem with capping as it will create peaks at the tails. So the most acceptable bias is to change outlier values to the mean of the feature distribution.
Since a lot of columns have very high number of outliers. To add to that if we drop all outliers then we lose the entire dataset. Also since if we cap outliers then columns will have more than one peak and hence will not be normally distributed. Further more the target variable class is already imbalanced. Hence we will deal with outliers in two ways:-
First we will remove rows with the highest number of outliers, making sure we choose rows only from the dominant class of the target variables. We will use this method as much as possible towards achieving class balance.
The rest of the outliers we will change into the mean of the column. Since the number of columns affected by this will be much reduced from the earlier conditions, hence we will bias the dataset the least in this way.
In [18]:
# Create an outliers dataframe which tracks how many outliers in each row
df_outliers = pd.DataFrame(np.unique(idx_list, return_counts=True), index=["idx", "freq"]).T

# Add target variable
df_outliers["Pass/Fail"] = df_signal["Pass/Fail"]

# Create a drop list based on undersampling dominant class
drop_list = df_outliers[df_outliers["Pass/Fail"] == 0].sort_values("freq", ascending=False).head(1069).index

# Drop records based on droplist
df_signal.drop(drop_list, inplace=True)

5. Model training, testing and tuning:¶

• Model training:¶
  • Pick up a supervised learning model.
  • Train the model.
  • Use cross validation techniques. Hint: Use all CV techniques that you have learnt in the course.
  • Apply hyper-parameter tuning techniques to get the best accuracy. Suggestion: Use all possible hyper parameter combinations to extract the best accuracies.
  • Use any other technique/method which can enhance the model performance. Hint: Dimensionality reduction, attribute removal, standardisation/normalisation, target balancing etc.
  • Display and explain the classification report in detail.
  • Design a method of your own to check if the achieved train and test accuracies might change if a different sample population can lead to new train and test accuracies. Hint: You can use your concepts learnt under Applied Statistics module.
  • Apply the above steps for all possible models that you have learnt so far.
The function in the cell below achieve the following:-
  • Use cross validation techniques. Hint: Use all CV techniques that you have learnt in the course.
  • Apply hyper-parameter tuning techniques to get the best accuracy. Suggestion: Use all possible hyper parameter combinations to extract the best accuracies.
  • Design a method of your own to check if the achieved train and test accuracies might change if a different sample population can lead to new train and test accuracies. Hint: You can use your concepts learnt under Applied Statistics module.
In [48]:
# Use cross validation techniques
# Apply hyper-parameter tuning techniques to get the best accuracy
def param_tuning(X, y, model, param, X_val, y_val):
    # Set the metrics for evaluation
    scoring = ['accuracy', 'recall','f1_macro']

    # creating a KFold object 
    folds = 3

    # Creating the grid search
    grid_search = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator = model,
                                     param_distributions = param, 
                                     n_iter = 100, 
                                     cv = folds, 
                                     verbose=10, 
                                     random_state=42, 
                                     n_jobs = -1,
                                     scoring= scoring,
                                     return_train_score=True,
                                     refit='accuracy')
    
    # fit the model
    grid_search.fit(X, y)
    
    # cv results
    cv_results = pd.DataFrame(grid_search.cv_results_)
    
    col_loc = list(cv_results.columns).index('params')
    df_analysis = cv_results.loc[cv_results["params"] == grid_search.best_params_, 
                                 cv_results.columns[col_loc:]]
    
    # Design a method of your own to check if the achieved train and test accuracies might change if a different sample population can lead to new train and test accuracies. 
    # Hint: You can use your concepts learnt under Applied Statistics module.
    # Join the validation dataset
    data = pd.concat([X_val, y_val], axis=1)

    # configure BOOTSTRAP Method learnt in Applied Statistics module.
    n_iterations = 1000              # Number of bootstrap samples to create
    n_size = int(len(data) * 1)    # picking only 100 % of the given data in every bootstrap sample
    
    # run bootstrap
    stats = list()
    for i in range(n_iterations):
        # prepare train and test sets
        index = resample(data.index, n_samples=n_size)   # Sampling with replacement
        train = data.loc[index].values
        test = data.loc[set(data.index) - set(index)].values   # picking rest of the data not considered in sample

        # fit model
        model.set_params(**grid_search.best_params_)
        model.fit(train[:,:-1], train[:,-1])
        
        # evaluate model
        predictions = model.predict(test[:,:-1])
        score = accuracy_score(test[:,-1], predictions)  
        stats.append(score)
    
    # plot scores
    plt.hist(stats)
    plt.show()
    # confidence intervals
    alpha = 0.9                             # for 90% confidence 
    p = ((1.0-alpha)/2.0) * 100              # tail regions on right and left .25 on each side indicated by P value (border)
    lower = max(0.0, np.percentile(stats, p))  
    p = (alpha+((1.0-alpha)/2.0)) * 100
    upper = min(1.0, np.percentile(stats, p))
    print('%.1f confidence interval %.1f%% and %.1f%%' % (alpha*100, lower*100, upper*100))
    
    # Populating the analysis datframe with statistical values from bootstrap
    df_analysis["lower_confidence"] = lower
    df_analysis["upper_confidence"] = upper
    df_analysis["mean"] = np.mean(stats)
    df_analysis["median"] = np.median(stats)
    df_analysis["std"] = np.std(stats)
    
#     ##################################### Saving backups
    
#     # Create Pickle file from the Random Forest Classifier(rf)
#     with open('_cv.pickle', 'wb') as dump_var:
#         pickle.dump(grid_search, dump_var)
        
#     import json

#     with open("bootstrap_stats.json", 'w') as f:
#         # indent=2 is not needed but makes the file human-readable
#         json.dump(stats, f, indent=2) 
    
    # Return the analysis dataframe
    return(df_analysis)

In [49]:
# Use any other technique/method which can enhance the model performance. 
# Hint: Dimensionality reduction, attribute removal, standardisation/normalisation, target balancing etc.
def dimension_reduction(X):
    # Initialise PCA
    pca = PCA(svd_solver='randomized', random_state=42)

    # Fit PCA to the required features after scaling
    pca.fit(X)

    # Display the screeplot to determine how many componenets to keep
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12, 8))
    plt.plot(np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_))
    plt.xlabel("Number of Components")
    plt.xticks(range(len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)), range(1, len(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)+1))
    plt.ylabel("Cumulative Explaince Variance")
    plt.title("Screeplot")
    plt.grid()
    plt.show()
    
    idx=0
    for x in pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:].cumsum():
        idx+=1
        if x > 0.9: break

    # Display amount of variance explained
    print("First %d components explain %2.5f%% of the variance of the selected features" 
          %(idx, sum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_[:idx])*100))

    # Reinitialising PCA with the required number of components
    pca = PCA(n_components=idx, svd_solver='randomized', random_state=42)

    # Assigning new features to the auto dataset and dropping compressed features
    return(pd.DataFrame(pca.fit_transform(X)), idx)

    df_new.rename(index={df_new.index[0]: key}, inplace=True)
    
    # Try adding new row to analysis dataframe
    try:
        df_analysis = pd.concat([df_new, df_analysis])
        
    # If analysis dataframe does not exist then make a new dataframe with new analysis
    except NameError:
        df_analysis = df_new.copy()

    model = dict_analysis[key][1]
    model.set_params(**list(df_new.params)[0])

    model.fit(X_val, y_val)
    pred = model.predict(X_train)

    print(classification_report(y_train, pred))

    confusion_matrix(y_train, pred)

import os
import pickle
import json

# Load training csv file into a dataframe
df_train = pd.read_csv("signal-data.csv")

# Seperate Dependent and Independent variables
y_final = df_train.pop("Pass/Fail")
X_final = df_train

# Rename target variable class
y_final = y_final.replace({-1: 0})

# Reload the Pickle
if os.path.getsize('final_model.pickle') > 0:
    # Load the Pickle file in the memory
    pickle_in = open('final_model.pickle', 'rb')
    pickle_clf = pickle.load(pickle_in)

# Reload column mask
with open("col_list.json", 'r') as f:
    mask = json.load(f)

# Fit pickled model to the masked train set
pickle_clf.fit(X_final[mask], y_final)

6. Conclusion and improvisation:¶

• Write your conclusion on the results¶
From observations made above, it seems that the data has some issues. There are very few records of one class while the other class is abundant (majority class is over 10 times the minority class). So when we split data to create a validation set the train set and validation stats test are not the same even if we stratify during splitting. This has the unfortunate result of making the two sets seem like they are from different populations. Hence it is not a correct way of validating our results or even conducting bootstrap to check confidence intervals.
Hence, I proceeded with the assignment despite the warnings. I answered the questions to the best of my ability. In conclusion, I would have worked on this dataset very differently :-
  • I might have kept the class imbalance but used metrics like recall, precision and AUC as evaluation metrics
  • Would have done some level of feature engineering but kept most of the columns, since the number of rows are also pretty high
  • Would have confirmed that 'curse of dimensions' was avoided
  • Would have used the Time column and extracted day, week, month etc information and used nearest neighbours regressor to predict the null values and to reshape outliers.
In short, there were a lot more things to try on this dataset, before I would blame the dataset (as I did right at the start of this piece). However, those paths remain unexplored.
